outlooksByWeek.1: Josh Allen's campaign opens with a seemingly soft Week 1 matchup when the Bills host the Cardinals. Arizona allowed 7.6 YPA last season and 32 touchdown passes while only registering 33 sacks. They didn't do much to address their weaknesses in the offseason, and look particularly vulnerable at cornerback. Allen will have to deal with the loss of top wide receiver Stefon Diggs, though the matchup suggests he'll hit the ground running both figuratively and literally with at least eight rushing touchdowns in all but one season as a pro.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen is back for his seventh season with the Bills. The dual-threat quarterback has been a fantasy dynamo over the past three seasons, averaging 24.7 fantasy points per game (best among QBs). Allen lost Stefon Diggs and Gabe Davis this offseason, which is notable because he averaged only 253.3 passing yards per game last season (his lowest since 2019) and he rushed for his fewest yards since 2020. He more than made up for the rushing decline with 15 rush TDs, which will be tough to repeat. It will be difficult to replace Diggs, but the team did add Curtis Samuel in free agency and Keon Coleman with the No. 33 pick in the draft. Allen is still firmly on the QB1 radar, but managers shouldn't be surprised if we see some regression in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Christian McCaffrey sustained a calf injury this offseason, but the 49ers have not expressed any concern that he won't be available against the Jets in Week 1. The Jets have one of the best defenses in the NFL and allowed just 3.99 yards per carry to running backs in 2023. That said, even the best defenses in the league have their hands full containing McCaffrey, a true workhorse back who racked up over 125 yards from scrimmage per game in 2023. Even with slightly lowered expectations in a tough matchup, McCaffrey remains a top shelf fantasy option this weekend.

player.seasonOutlook: McCaffrey recorded the most fantasy points per game (24.5) and the third-most fantasy points overall (391) among all players last season. He ranked inside the top three fantasy producers at the position in nearly every statistical category -- from rushing yards (1,459, RB1) and receiving yards (564, RB2) to evaded tackles (77, RB1) and total TDs (21, RB1) -- the 28-year-old stayed healthy for a second straight season. McCaffrey is the centerpiece of the 49ers' explosive offense and he deserves to be at the top of draft boards this summer.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jalen Hurts is coming off career-bests of 23 touchdown passes and 15 touchdown runs in 2023 for the Eagles.  However, he also turned the ball over 19 times, 15 of which came via the interception.  Hurts has yet another weapon to lean on in the form of Saquon Barkley, so while Hurts could lose a couple of touchdowns on the ground, he should benefit overall from the presence of another playmaker on offense.  In Week 1, Hurts will face a Green Bay defense that was better against the pass than the run in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: Hurts comes off his best NFL season, thanks mainly to 15 rushing touchdowns, tying Josh Allen for the most among QBs. In fact, no other QBs reached seven rushing scores. Hurts finished behind only Allen in fantasy points at the position despite playing the final months with a knee injury, as the Eagles collapsed down the stretch. Don't blame Hurts. He averaged 21.5 fantasy points from Weeks 15 through 17, before sitting most of the finale. The Eagles lost C Jason Kelce, but the offensive line and wide receiver options remain top-notch, and the controversial "tush push" play Hurts feasts on remains legal. Expect another fantastic statistical season, and a legitimate chance to finish as fantasy's top scorer.

outlooksByWeek.1: CeeDee Lamb is fresh off a lucrative contract extension and should be primed for another huge season in Dallas as the undisputed top option.  Dak Prescott returns under center, and the tandem connected for career-best numbers for Lamb in 2023.  Lamb caught a staggering 135 passes for 1,749 yards and 12 touchdowns.  With a lackluster running game and limited depth behind Lamb at wideout, the star wideout should see all the opportunities he can handle.  Unfortunately, Week 1 may provide a stiff test, as Lamb not only may not be in game shape yet due to signing the extension late, but Dallas will also face a Cleveland pass defense that allowed the fewest yards in the NFL last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Lamb led the entire fantasy football world in fantasy points last season, surpassing 25 points in eight games and truly dominating the second half of the season. Lamb started slow -- a career theme, actually -- but from Week 8 on, he averaged 28.5 fantasy points per game. His 313.6 fantasy points in the final 11 weeks alone topped the full-season performance of all but nine NFL players. Lamb is not only a clear top-five fantasy pick, but with his durability and the Cowboys' high-octane offense, one can make the case for him as a solid choice to go No. 1 overall.

outlooksByWeek.1: Lamar Jackson posted the highest yards per attempt and completion rate of his career in 2023, his first under offensive coordinator Todd Monken. That was good enough for him to win his second MVP Award and he'll now lead Baltimore into a Week 1 matchup against a stout Chiefs defense. The secondary has had some turnover between the losses of L'Jarius Sneed and Mike Edwards, but there's still athleticism at all levels of the unit. That athleticism could serve to limit Jackson's usefulness on the ground, though the Ravens will undoubtedly have to utilize an aggressive offensive approach to keep pace with Patrick Mahomes. That should lead to serviceable statistical output for Jackson to begin 2024.

player.seasonOutlook: The reigning NFL MVP enters his seventh pro season as one of the league's most dynamic players at the position. In 2023, working under new offensive coordinator Todd Monken, Jackson played in 16 games, posting a career high in pass yards, while leading all quarterbacks in rushing. He averaged 20.7 fantasy points per game, finishing as QB4 in total points. With a strong supporting cast led by tight end Mark Andrews, wide receiver Zay Flowers and running back Derrick Henry, plus a system that maximizes his elite dual-threat ability, Jackson should once again produce top-tier fantasy numbers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tyreek Hill looks to pop off for the Dolphins in Week 1 against Jacksonville. Hill is off consecutive 1,700 yard seasons, and averaged 15.1 ypc last season at 29 years old, the second-highest mark of his career. He's scored at least seven touchdowns every year since his rookie campaign, and it wasn't just big plays last year, as Hill had five catches in all but two games and was held below 58 yards once. Jacksonville allowed a moderate 7.1 ypa, but ranked third to last in surrendering catches of 40+ yards a season ago and had the eighth fewest sacks, suggesting time to throw and for Hill to get downfield.

player.seasonOutlook: Hill enters his third season with the Dolphins after another exquisite season, in which he averaged 10.7 targets and 23.5 fantasy points per game. Hill was one of only eight players in the league who had at least 90 receptions and 1,200 receiving yards last season. Targets are among the most predictable year-to-year counting stats for wide receivers, and he remains the top option in a Dolphins offense that ranked second in passing yards in 2023, a trend that's expected to continue. Despite Hill entering his age-30 season, he should still be one of the first receivers selected in fantasy drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: Patrick Mahomes is coming off what was by his standards a disappointing 2023 regular season, as his 4,183 passing yards and 27 passing touchdowns were his lowest totals since 2019, when he played only 14 games. Kansas City didn't rest on its laurels as back-to-back Super Bowl champions though, working to inject more speed into its receiving corps by signing Marquise Brown and selecting Xavier Worthy with the 28th overall pick in the 2024 Draft. While more downfield threats will be welcome, Mahomes will still have veteran tight end Travis Kelce as his primary target, and second-year wideout Rashee Rice as a yard-after-catch merchant on underneath routes and bubble screens. Mahomes will look to begin a bounce-back campaign in Week 1 against a tough Ravens defense that ranked first in the league in 2023 in yards per attempt allowed, and tied for second in passing touchdowns allowed.

player.seasonOutlook: Though Mahomes' 2023 saw him post his worst yards per attempt (7.0), aDOT (6.2), touchdown (4.5%) and interception (2.3%) rates of his six seasons as an NFL regular, consider the context: He was working with his weakest set of receivers in any of those years. The Chiefs were worst in the league in drops (38) and had the second-worst catch rate on throws 20-plus yards downfield (27.4%), after having been seventh best in that department the season before. Mahomes made it work -- he led the team to a Super Bowl title, after all -- and it's a testament to his overwhelming, Hall of Fame-caliber talent that he finished eighth among quarterbacks in scoring in spite of his supporting cast. The additions of Marquise Brown and Xavier Worthy, coupled with Rashee Rice's late-season emergence, should give Mahomes the weapons necessary to rebound as a top-five positional pick and early-round selection.

outlooksByWeek.1: Amon-Ra St. Brown has seen his production rise steadily each season since being drafted in 2021, setting career highs in catches, yards, targets, and touchdowns last year. He accounted for nearly 30 percent of the Lions' targets in 2023, finishing in the top-five league-wide in each category. With star rookie TE Sam LaPorta and other receivers in the mix, St. Brown remains the primary pass-catching option, excelling in both short-area and yards-after-catch situations. He faces a Rams defense in Week 1 that allowed 246.8 passing yards per game last season, ranking 20th in the NFL. St. Brown's significant target share and consistent performance make him an elite fantasy option each week, regardless of the matchup.

player.seasonOutlook: After inking a new 4-year contract this offseason, St. Brown returns as the leader of the Lions' receiving corps. One of most consistent wide receivers in fantasy, ARSB had an outstanding 11 games with at least 18 fantasy points in 2023. No wide receiver had more top-20 weekly finishes and only Tyreek Hill had more weeks finishing seventh or better. Possessing both a high floor and ceiling, St. Brown was top five in every major receiving category last season and returns to an offense that looks to be just as potent this season. St. Brown is showing no signs of slowing down, and is poised to be a top-five fantasy wide receiver in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Joe Burrow appears to be fully recovered from wrist surgery that ended his 2023 season prematurely and will lead the Bengals into a Week 1 matchup against New England. However, there's still a cloud over the Cincinnati offense as Ja'Marr Chase continues his hold-in, leaving his status murky for the game and potentially leaving Burrow without his top pass catcher. The New England secondary also has the chance to be respectable as both Jonathan Jones and Christian Gonzalez are capable players in coverage. That makes Burrow something of a risky start, though he's topped 30 passing touchdowns in each of his last two full seasons.

player.seasonOutlook: Heading into his fifth pro season, Burrow looks to rebound after an injury-plagued 2023 that limited his production and availability. A calf injury during training camp forced Burrow to miss practice time, while a wrist injury in Week 11 shut him down for the season. From Weeks 1-4, with Burrow clearly still impacted by the calf injury, he averaged only 7.9 fantasy points per game. However, from Weeks 5-10, he posted three games of 22 or more points, with an average of 21.4 points during that stretch. With two big-play receivers in Ja'Marr Chase and Tee Higgins, a healthy Burrow should be in the mix to produce top-five quarterback numbers in the Bengals' pass-heavy offense.

outlooksByWeek.1: C.J. Stroud's sophomore season begins on the road against the AFC South rival Colts in Week 1. Stroud threw for 4,108 yards with a 23:5 TD:INT in a highly successful rookie regular season for the Texans after being selected second overall in the 2023 NFL Draft. That success included 648 yards and a 4:0 TD:INT in two games against the Colts, whom the Texans beat on the road in Week 18 last season with a playoff berth on the line. Houston traded for six-time 1,000-yard receiver Stefon Diggs while bringing back its top three receiving yards leaders from last season (WRs Nico Collins and Tank Dell, plus TE Dalton Schultz). Indianapolis allowed the fifth-most points per game last season (24.4) and didn't make significant personnel changes on defense, bringing back all 10 players that made double-digit starts on that side of the ball.

player.seasonOutlook: The former Buckeye looks to build on a momentous first season that included becoming just the fifth rookie quarterback to ever throw for at least 4,000 yards. Without much rushing volume or success in either his collegiate or professional profile, Stroud's fantasy production will be defined by his proficiency from the pocket. After finishing seventh in per-game fantasy output last season, another prolific passing season could unfold given the presence of a trio of talented receivers -- Nico Collins, Stefon Diggs and Tank Dell -- each of whom brings special route trees and skill sets to the field. Securing Stroud in the middle rounds is a sound strategy for those who wait a bit at the position.

outlooksByWeek.1: Anthony Richardson kicks off his second NFL season with a Week 1 home game against the Texans, who allowed the 10th-most passing yards per game in 2023. The fourth overall pick in the 2023 NFL Draft had three passing touchdowns and four rushing touchdowns in four games before suffering a season-ending shoulder injury in Week 5 of his rookie season. Richardson's dual-threat skill set coupled with star RB Jonathan Taylor gives the Colts' rushing attack immense upside, but questions remain about the big-armed QB's accuracy as a passer. Even if Josh Downs (ankle) is unavailable against Houston, the addition of rookie second-round pick Adonai Mitchell to holdovers Michael Pittman and Alec Pierce in the wide receiver room gives Richardson plenty of weapons in the passing game. The Texans have five new projected starters on defense.

player.seasonOutlook: Football fans are rightfully excited for this dual-threat signal-caller's second season. From Cam Newton to Josh Allen, Lamar Jackson and Jalen Hurts, there is a growing legacy of young quarterbacks thriving as fantasy forces thanks to what some deem the cheat code: Rushing for immense value from behind center. Based on his first three games in the NFL, Richardson was on pace for more than 700 rushing yards with double-digit touchdown production on the ground. After missing 13 games due to a shoulder injury, the natural question is whether Richardson's play style is sustainable on this hard-hitting stage. What isn't in doubt is whether the versatile talent is capable of delivering fun fantasy lines, as last year's small sample suggests is entirely possible. The risks are real, yet the rewards of drafting Richardson as a QB1 in the early-to-middle rounds could be league-altering.

outlooksByWeek.1: Bijan Robinson was surprisingly underutilized as a rookie last season, but beginning with Atlanta's matchup against a tough Steelers front in Week 1, he now projects for the workhorse role that his 215-plus pound, and 4.46-second 40 build and former No. 8 overall draft capital demands. Pittsburgh is a tough Week 1 opponent that last season was more vulnerable through the air than up front, but Robinson's three-down skillset makes him capable of overcoming even the most difficult matchups. In addition to working as Atlanta's top ball carrier, with Tyler Allgeier now relegated to a true backup role, Robinson could do most of his damage Week 1 as one of new quarterback Kirk Cousins' favorite pass-catchers in the intermediate area of the field.

player.seasonOutlook: Robinson's rookie season was a mixed bag that included limited rushing contributions (15th or lower in carries, yards and TDs) but excellent receiving production (top five among RBs in routes, targets, yards and TDs), as well as terrific efficiency. Robinson's season felt underwhelming considering his early-first-round pedigree, but he finished fifth among RBs in snaps, sixth in yards and ninth in fantasy points. With Kirk Cousins now under center and Zac Robinson replacing run-heavy Arthur Smith as the team's play caller, a leap forward for Robinson seems likely in his second campaign. That will especially be the case if he manages more work near the goal line (only two carries inside the 5-yard line in 2023). Robinson should be one of the first RBs off the board on draft day.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jordan Love aims to build on his breakout 2023 campaign as the Packers travel to SAo Paulo, Brazil for a Week 1 matchup against an Eagles defense that ranked 31st in the NFL last year. Love threw for 4,159 yards and 32 touchdowns in his first full season as Green Bay's QB. With dynamic targets like Jayden Reed, Christian Watson, Romeo Doubs and Dontayvion Wicks, Love and head coach Matt LaFleur have plenty of options in their passing attack. Although Philadelphia brought in defensive guru Vic Fangio as their new defensive coordinator in the offseason, expect Love to take advantage of an Eagles secondary that allowed 35 TD passes last season, 31st in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Love returns as Green Bay's quarterback after leading the Packers to the playoffs as a first-year starter in 2023. While expectations were low considering his limited NFL action and young supporting cast, Love proved doubters wrong by finishing as fantasy's QB7. That includes six top-10 finishes in his final eight games. Love was eighth or better in passing yards, attempts, completions and aDOT, while also finishing second in passing touchdowns and posting a 3-to-1 TD/INT ratio. Love could use his legs a little more, but with his success in 2023 and all of his exciting, young pass-catchers returning, Love should be viewed as a fringe QB1 in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Justin Jefferson kicks off the 2024 season looking to build on another stellar campaign despite battling injuries last year. Even with the uncertainty at quarterback, Jefferson remains a premier fantasy option thanks to his exceptional production, finishing Top 10 in yards per route in all four of his seasons. He'll be heavily relied upon as Sam Darnold's primary target in a Minnesota offense that may lean on its star receiver more than ever. Jefferson gets a favorable matchup in Week 1, facing a Giants defense that allowed the fifth-most fantasy points to wide receivers last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Jefferson enters his fifth season with the Vikings after missing significant time due to injury for the first time in his career last season. In his eight healthy games, Jefferson averaged 24 fantasy points per game and was one of only four wide receivers to have at least six games with 23 fantasy points in 2023. In a season where the Vikings started Kirk Cousins, Nick Mullens, Joshua Dobbs and Jaren Hall, Jefferson proved himself QB-proof. This season he'll have Sam Darnold under center. While there could be some growing pains in this offense, Jefferson is one of the few WRs that can make magic happen with subpar QB play. He is once again a top-five fantasy wide receiver.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ja'Marr Chase enjoyed a productive 2023 season despite playing half of it with backup quarterback Jake Browning. There's little left for him to prove to cement his status as one of the top wide receivers in the game, though his status for the Bengals' Week 1 matchup against the Patriots is less clear. Chase has held out from the majority of training camp while seeking a new contract, and he has yet to practice leading up to the team's regular season opener. If he does suit up, he could face a pitch count, though he'd still likely be worth starting due to his explosive playmaking ability.

player.seasonOutlook: Chase starts his fourth pro season with the Bengals looking to boost his numbers with a healthy Joe Burrow back running the offense. Chase averaged 16.4 fantasy PPG, down from the 20.0 PPG he registered in 2022 (WR3). However, Chase still posted five games with 20 or more points, including the 52.2-point performance in Week 5 versus the Cardinals. Chase has totaled 29 touchdowns in his career and is one the league's premier players at the position due to his big-play ability and upper-tier play strength. Lock him in as a top 10 player overall in fantasy this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Breece Hall enters Week 1 as a clear workhorse for the Jets as they prepare to face the 49ers on Monday night. Hall closed 2023 with 70 carries across his final three games, while catching an impressive 76 balls during his sophomore campaign. It's a challenging matchup, as San Francisco allowed the third fewest rushing yards and fourth fewest rushing touchdowns a season ago, but his volume shouldn't be questioned. Far from a smash situation, Hall is positioned to enjoy a heavy workload that can lead to upside.

player.seasonOutlook: Hall appeared fully recovered from his ACL tear by the end of the 2023 season. He was one of the few bright spots in a struggling Jets offense that was without future Hall of Fame quarterback Aaron Rodgers. From Week 5 on, Hall was no longer on a snap count and his usage increased significantly, as he averaged 20.5 touches and 20.2 fantasy points per game over the final 13 games. Despite the Jets' offense ranking 29th in run block win rate, Hall consistently produced and also led all running backs in targets, receptions and receiving yards. Hall's potential is even greater with Rodgers hopefully under center for the entire 2024 season. Fantasy managers should feel confident drafting him as the second running back off the board, behind Christian McCaffrey.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kyler Murray starts the season with a Week 1 showdown against a Bills defense that had 16 interceptions in 2023, tied for 6th most in the league. The Cardinals gave Murray a premium new receiving weapon in rookie Marvin Harrison, and he still gets to take advantage of one of the best receiving tight ends in the league in Trey McBride. Murray might rush and scramble a bit more this season now that he is a year and a half removed from his ACL surgery, which would be a nice boost to his fantasy floor. With Harrison now in the fold, the Cardinals 27th ranked passing offense last year should improve, but it's a very tough matchup in Buffalo. The Bills defense lost some key players in the secondary this offseason, but they are typically one of the stronger pass defenses in the league, ranking 6th in passing yards allowed last year.

player.seasonOutlook: Murray returned as the Cardinals' starter after being sidelined for 11 months due to a right knee injury that he suffered in December 2022. Murray's rehab proved successful, as the dual-threat talent immediately flashed his trademark wheels, averaging more than 30 rushing yards per game between Weeks 10 and 18 last season. He was less consistent as a passer, recording his lowest completion percentage since his 2019 rookie campaign. A considerable amount of his inefficiency, however, could be attributed to a dearth of surrounding talent, as well as Marquise Brown's end-of-season absence (heel). Murray heads into his sixth pro campaign with a full offseason under his belt and plenty of time to build rapport with the team's young pass-catching talent, including fourth overall pick Marvin Harrison Jr. Consider Murray a low-end QB1 for fantasy purposes.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jayden Daniels has been handed the keys to the offense for Washington as a rookie.  The Heisman Trophy winner is an elite athlete and can torment the opposition with both his legs as well as his arm.  Certainly a learning curve for the rookie is possible, but expectations are extremely high, and the buzz surrounding Daniels this preseason is that he has the look and feel of a future star.  In Week 1, Daniels will face a Buccaneers defense that struggled against the pass in 2023, but excelled against the run, meaning Daniels could be forced to play the role of a pocket passer in his NFL debut.

player.seasonOutlook: Daniels was selected second overall by the Commanders in April's draft, and he may be more valuable in fantasy than the quarterback who went first (Caleb Williams), thanks to his elite running ability. Daniels not only compiled 10 times as many touchdown passes as interceptions while winning the Heisman Trophy in 2023, he also rushed for more than 1,100 yards and 10 more scores. Washington is a good landing spot for Daniels, with savant Kliff Kingsbury directing the offense and ample offensive options around him. Daniels probably slips outside the QB1 options on draft day, but he may end up there by season's end.

outlooksByWeek.1: Alvin Kamara enters his eighth season with the Saints with a favorable Week 1 matchup against Carolina on deck, and as this team's unquestioned top backfield option. While Kamara's rushing totals have dropped every year since 2020, it's notable that his one game against the Panthers last season was his most efficient of the year, at 4.7 yards per carry. New Orleans' offensive line has lost three starters in Andrus Peat, James Hurst and Ryan Ramczyk from last season, and though that could hamper Kamara's efficiency as a rusher, it could paradoxically boost his production if Derek Carr is forced to regularly pivot plays towards an emergency dump-off pass. Kamara buoyed his production with 75 receptions in 13 game last season, and as efficiency is no longer his call to fame, volume may have to do for the 29-year-old this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Kamara had a career-low 694 rush yards on just 3.9 yards per carry last season, but he was still an effective receiver (75 receptions) despite being 29 years old, and he finished as RB11. He was able to hold off rookie Kendre Miller, who was often injured last season, but we expect Miller to make a bigger impact this season. The versatile Taysom Hill is also probably going to eat into Kamara's production, further clouding his outlook. Kamara was ninth in the league in red zone touches and should still be a go-to option, but the days of him being one of the first RBs off the board are over. He's now a low-end RB1, and the aforementioned TD vultures will be bothersome to his fantasy managers this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Baker Mayfield and the Buccaneers' offense will look to build off last season's momentum at home against the Commanders in Week 1. In 2023, Mayfield resurrected his NFL career by setting new personal-best marks with 4,044 passing yards and 28 touchdowns, though as a result of that success former offensive coordinator Dave Canales was poached to become the Panthers' head coach. Mayfield now pairs with new OC Liam Coen for a juicy matchup against a Washington defense that ranked last in both points allowed and yards allowed last season, and which lost standout CB Kendall Fuller over the offseason. Courtesy of a bolstered interior O-line, Mayfield should have adequate protection from DTs Daron Payne and Jonathan Allen. Add in the addition of third-round pick Jalen McMillan, plus an offense more willing to utilize pre-snap motion, and Mayfield is in position to air it out Week 1.

player.seasonOutlook: Mayfield enjoyed a resurgence in 2023, appearing in all 17 of Tampa Bay's games and finishing no lower than 10th in pass attempts, completions, yards, TDs and fantasy points. The latter includes some survivor bias (he was 18th on a per-game basis), which was due to limited rushing production (outside the top 20 in both rushing yards and TDs). Mayfield has never been a rushing factor and his supporting cast remains roughly the same as it was in 2023, so especially considering he's never finished better than 18th in PPG, he's best viewed as a low-ceiling QB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Saquon Barkley stays in the NFC East with a move from the bumbling Giants to Super Bowl contender Philadelphia.  Barkley was injury-prone during his time with the G-Men, but still maintained his explosiveness when healthy, and should benefit from a bevy of weapons around him on the Eagles, rather than being the sole focal point of a mediocre offense as he was in New York.  In Week 1, Barkley will have an extremely favorable matchup versus a  Packers defense that allowed 128.3 rushing yards per tilt in 2023, which was 28th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley left the rival Giants for the superior offense down the New Jersey Turnpike, one stacked with elite options at quarterback, wide receiver and, perhaps most importantly, along the still-dominant offensive line. Barkley's 2023 numbers may appear average, but blame the underwhelming New York offense, from the players to its direction. Still blessed with elite skills, a mostly healthy Barkley finished ninth among running backs at 15.9 fantasy points per game, and he may return to his 2022 numbers (1,312 rushing yards, 57 catches) in this top offense. Barkley is a first-round fantasy pick and potential top-three fantasy RB provided health (one never knows) and volume (no problems there).

outlooksByWeek.1: James Cook will look to pick up where he left off for the Bills in a Week 1 matchup against the Cardinals. He recorded double-digit carries in the final 10 games, leading to a 1,122-yard sophomore campaign while adding a solid 44 receptions. The downside is that Cook only ran for two touchdowns while Josh Allen got 15. While you wouldn't expect Allen to replicate that, Buffalo added Ray Davis to their backfield via the draft who offers more size and power that can be used closer to the goal line. Cook's volume should remain steady and the matchup to open the year couldn't be softer as Arizona gave up the most rushing yards in the league in 2023 and didn't substantially upgrade defensively. We just need to see more scoring chances for Cook for him to take off.

player.seasonOutlook: Cook returns to the gridiron for his third season with the Bills. He finished as RB12 in fantasy last season and ranked fourth in the league in rushing yards. Joe Brady replacing Ken Dorsey as offensive coordinator was a godsend for Cook. From Weeks 11 through 18, Cook averaged and impressive 19.6 touches and 16.4 fantasy points per game. Since Cook is the undisputed leader of the Bills' backfield, we can expect a similar workload from him in 2024. He can be safely drafted as a high-end RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Caleb Williams, the No. 1 overall pick in the 2024 draft, begins his career with the Bears as the franchise quarterback. Surrounded by an upgraded cast that includes wideouts DJ Moore, Keenan Allen, and rookie Rome Odunze, as well as pass-catching back D'Andre Swift and steady tight end Cole Kmet, Williams has a wealth of weapons at his disposal. His elite arm and mobility make him a dynamic playmaker with the potential to become the Bears' first 4,000-yard passer in franchise history. In Week 1, Williams will debut at Soldier Field against the Titans, a defense that allowed the 11th-fewest fantasy points to opposing QBs but accumulated the fewest interceptions in the league last season.

player.seasonOutlook: The Bears selected Williams with the first pick in the 2024 NFL draft. He was stellar at USC, showcasing his natural playmaking ability both in and out of the pocket, finishing with a single-season school record with 4,919 yards passing. In Chicago, he joins an offense that was second in rushing yards and attempts while also finishing bottom six in passing yards, passing attempts and completions last season. Part of that rushing total came from the departed Justin Fields, and Shane Waldron is now calling plays, so this offense should be more balanced in 2024. Williams will have a strong supporting cast with DJ Moore, Keenan Allen and Rome Odunze leading the way, but he's best viewed as a mid-tier QB2 with upside in his rookie season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Geno Smith looks to rebound from a somewhat disappointing 2023 with a Week 1 home matchup against a Broncos defense that ranked 29th in the league last season. New Seahawks offensive coordinator Ryan Grubb is expected to give Smith plenty of opportunities to stretch the field, playing into his strengths as a strong-armed passer. With DK Metcalf, Tyler Lockett and Jaxon Smith-Njigba at wide receiver, Smith has enough weapons to take advantage of the Broncos. Denver made few offseason moves to improve a defense that allowed 29 TD passes last season, fifth in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Author of one of the greatest script flips of the 2022 season, Smith was met with cautious optimism by fantasy managers who were unsure of his ability to duplicate a top-five fantasy finish at QB again in 2023. As expected, Smith's numbers regressed. Most disappointing was his dip in scoring, as the 33-year-old passed for just 20 TDs last season (down from 30). Smith finished the season just inside the top 20 fantasy producers at the position, averaging a little more than 15 fantasy points per game. He figures to rebound slightly with new offensive coordinator Ryan Grubb bringing an uptempo approach and further integration of Jaxon Smith-Njigba to the team, but remains best utilized as a QB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: A.J. Brown topped 100 receptions for the first time in his NFL career last season for the Eagles, while also nearly gaining 1,500 yards for the second-straight year. However, he managed just seven touchdowns and averaged a career-low 13.7 yards per grab. Nevertheless, Brown remains as explosive as ever, and the Philadelphia offense should be even better with Saquon Barkley in the fold at running back.  In Week 1, Brown may face a difficult matchup shadowed by Jaire Alexander of the Packers, though, and Green Bay allowed just 206.8 passing yards per tilt in 2023, which was ninth in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Brown's second season in Philadelphia statistically mirrored his excellent debut, as he was fifth in receiving yards and provided a cool 17 fantasy points per game, eighth among wide receivers. The way Brown statistically achieved his numbers was a bit disturbing for fantasy managers (and the stumbling Eagles), as he dominated over a six-game stretch early on, averaging 138.5 receiving yards and tallying five touchdowns from Weeks 3 through 8, then reaching 100 yards in just one of the final nine contests. Still, QB Jalen Hurts leads an elite offense, and even with WR DeVonta Smith and new RB Saquon Barkley in the mix, Brown will see ample targets and end zone opportunities. Expect another season as a WR1 option and potential first-round choice.

outlooksByWeek.1: Puka Nacua has been a full participant in recent practices after suffering a knee injury in early August, and he is ready to start for the Rams in Week 1 at the Lions. While Detroit added much needed help to their secondary this offseason, they have a long way to go after allowing 28 receiving touchdowns in 2023, sixth worst in the NFL.  The return of a healthy Cooper Kupp might hurt Nacua's ceiling somewhat, but he still averaged over 8 targets per game when Kupp was active last season. Nacua remains a strong fantasy option to open the season.

player.seasonOutlook: Rostered in just 1.6% of ESPN Fantasy leagues ahead of Week 1 last season, Nacua proved to be the waiver wire's most generous offering. The first-year slotman immediately filled injured Cooper Kupp's shoes to lead the team in routes, targets, catches and yards, while regularly dazzling after the catch (639 YAC, WR5). Nacua's volume dipped after Kupp returned, but the BYU product continued to churn, setting both the NFL rookie receiving yards and receptions records. Given Kupp's age and injury history, Nacua is a good bet to remain Matthew Stafford's most productive pass-catcher again in 2024. He's a solid fantasy WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Rachaad White's third season with the Buccaneers kicks off at home against a vulnerable Washington defense Week 1. After having been a big part of Tampa Bay's offensive resurgence last season, White remains locked in as the top option in the backfield. His efficiency as a pass-catcher was elite in 2023, securing 64 of 70 targets for 549 yards and three touchdowns, and the Commanders' defense ranked dead last in the NFL last season in both points and yards allowed. The Buccaneers' upgrades to the interior of the O-line could now position White to take a step forward as a rusher, which was one area he struggled last season, and at 6-0, 214 pounds, he still profiles as the better goal-line option compared to rookie fourth-round pick Bucky Irving (5-9, 192 pounds).

player.seasonOutlook: White returns as the lead back in Tampa, entering his third season. He was the RB4 in fantasy scoring last season, racking up solid rushing yards, showing off his receiving skills and scoring nine total touchdowns. The Bucs made minimal changes behind White on the depth chart this offseason, with fourth-round pick Bucky Irving the most notable addition. Irving could earn his way into some work, but White outperformed expectations last season and should maintain a featured role. White has the look of a value pick once the big names are off the board in your league.

outlooksByWeek.1: Justin Herbert is coming off the worst season of his NFL career, as he missed four games due to a finger injury and set career lows with a 65.1 percent completion percentage, 3.134 passing yards and just 20 passing touchdowns. Things aren't pointed in the right direction for 2024, either. Herbert battled a plantar fascia issue in training camp which threatens to limit his mobility, and the Chargers' switch to Jim Harbaugh as head coach and Greg Roman as offensive coordinator should bring a much more run-heavy approach, denying the quarterback the high volume he's accustomed to. Herbert figures to be under center in Week 1 despite the foot injury, but he'll be facing a Raiders defense that finished in the top half of the league last year in passing yards and passing TDs allowed.

player.seasonOutlook: While Herbert is one of the league's most talented quarterbacks, he is saddled with starting for a Jim Harbaugh rebuild that's precariously thin on receiving talent. In the past three seasons, Herbert is third in passing yards per game (274.1), fourth among qualifiers in Total QBR (65.3) and he has averaged 19.1 fantasy points per game. That latter number placed eighth at the position, in large part because Herbert couldn't get things done behind a sputtering running game and with Mike Williams and Keenan Allen missing time due to injury in 2023. Allen and Williams are now elsewhere, and Harbaugh appears committed to a run-oriented offense. Herbert might struggle to deliver the fantasy goods, making him more of a matchup play for 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jared Goff enters the season having finished 2023 as a top-seven fantasy QB last year, benefiting from a high-volume Lions passing offense led by offensive coordinator Ben Johnson. Goff faces the Rams on Sunday Night Football in Week 1, a rematch of last year's Wild Card game. Despite a low average depth of target, Goff's efficiency and volume make him a strong fantasy play. The Rams allowed the seventh-most fantasy points per game to quarterbacks last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Jared Goff returns as the Lions' starter after his best season in the Motor City. In 2023, he was second in passing yards, attempts and completions, and fourth in passing TDs. In fact, Goff is the only QB to have at least 4,400 passing yards and 29 passing TDs in each of the past two seasons. However, he offers virtually zero in the rushing department (94 total rushing yards over that same two-season span). As a result, Goff finished 10 weeks as QB12 or lower in fantasy points despite his passing prowess and Detroit's high-octane offense. Goff is best viewed as a mid-range QB2 in Detroit's run-first scheme.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jonathan Taylor is healthy and ready to lead Indianapolis' backfield in Week 1 against a Texans defense that allowed the sixth-fewest rushing yards to running backs in 2023. An ankle injury landed Taylor on the PUP list amid a contract dispute to begin last season, but he produced six touchdowns in his final five appearances last season, which culminated with a 188-yard performance on the ground in a season-ending loss to Houston. Questions still linger about mobile QB Anthony Richardson's proficiency as a passer, so the Colts are expected to lean heavily on the ground game, even against the stout Texans front. Taylor faces minimal competition for backfield touches, as backup Trey Sermon is nursing a hamstring injury and third-stringer Tyler Goodson has just 87 career rushing yards.

player.seasonOutlook: An appraisal of Taylor's four-year career thus far shows his epic, All-Pro 2021 effort as an outlier of sorts. His other three NFL seasons include rushing outcomes between 74.1 and 78.3 yards per game and a total of 24 scores in 36 games, painting a picture of a strong RB1 candidate, just not the RB1 overall. It's worth noting we've yet to see Taylor take handoffs from Anthony Richardson, a reality that presents a blend of mystery and upside ahead of this season. With an unproven collection of backs behind him on the depth chart and the potential for a league-leading touch tally, Taylor remains a worthy early-round fantasy pick, even if that 2021 opus isn't the appropriate expectation.

outlooksByWeek.1: Daniel Jones and the Giants will look to silence the naysayers in Week 1 versus the Minnesota Vikings.  Jones had an inconsistent, injury-plagued 2023 campaign, but the front office bolstered the offensive line through free agency.  The G-Men also added a No. 1 wideout in the form of Malik Nabers, so there appear to be no more excuses for Jones.  He'll face a Minnesota defense that was mediocre at best against the pass in 2023, allowing 234.5 passing yards per tilt, which was 24th in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Jones was a surprise top-10 fantasy QB in 2022, thanks mostly to health and running prowess (seven TDs). The 2023 season hardly went as well. Jones tossed six interceptions in the first four games -- one more than he had the prior season over 16 games -- and then things got worse. He missed three games due to a neck injury, only to return briefly in Week 9 and tear his right ACL. Jones accounted for three touchdowns in six games, and the New York offense played better without him. He expects to be fully cleared for training camp, and his contract all but guarantees playing time. Fantasy managers should be mighty wary, even in superflex formats, and consider choosing at least 20 other quarterbacks first.

outlooksByWeek.1: Dak Prescott is coming off arguably his best season for the Cowboys.  Despite the lack of postseason success, Prescott has shined otherwise, throwing for over 4,500 yards for the second time in his career, surpassing 35 passing touchdowns while limiting his interceptions (just nine in 2023). Prescott likely also gave a huge sigh of relief when CeeDee Lamb was re-signed to a massive deal.  However, in Week 1, Dallas will likely face a stiff test versus a Cleveland defense that allowed the fewest passing yards in the NFL in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: Prescott bounced back last season after a challenging 2022, finishing third among QBs in fantasy points, and he was one of only four passers to average 20 fantasy points per game. Volume is key. No quarterback completed more passes and Prescott's 36 touchdown passes were four more than anyone else. While Prescott's long-term future in Dallas may be problematic, he is safe this season and enjoys CeeDee Lamb to throw to. Prescott has delivered exceptional statistics when healthy (2019, 2021, 2023), so while he may slip outside the top five quarterbacks on draft day, it only makes him a bargain.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brock Purdy faces a Jets defense in Week 1 that was one of the league's best last season, allowing less than 190 passing yards per game in 2023. Kyle Shannahan likely will continue to rely on an intermediate passing game where Purdy gets the ball into the hands of the many 49ers playmakers who are skilled at earning yards after the catch. Brandon Aiyuk finally re-signed, ending his offseason holdout and giving Purdy a full arsenal of receiving options. Purdy likely won't throw deep much in this matchup, but if he receivers get loose, he could put up decent numbers.

player.seasonOutlook: Purdy returned from UCL surgery by fending off (theoretical) competition at the position and putting together a breakout effort in 2023. Surrounded by elite YAC talent, serving in an ultra-friendly scheme and buoyed by a solid defense, Mr. Irrelevant didn't always have to do a whole lot to win games. That sometimes meant underwhelming numbers from a fantasy perspective, though Purdy did average more than 18 fantasy points per contest and finished inside the top 10 among fantasy QBs. He's not the most dynamic player, but his situation provides him (and fake football managers) with a wonderfully high floor. He projects to post fringe-QB1 fantasy numbers again in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jahmyr Gibbs enters his second season as the Lions' lead back after a strong rookie year, showcasing his ability as both a runner (5.2 YPC, 10 TDs) and a receiver. With David Montgomery likely serving as the 1B option, Gibbs is positioned to be the primary playmaker in the backfield. Detroit's excellent offensive line will continue to create opportunities, though Gibbs might see fewer goal-line carries due to Montgomery's power-running role. In Week 1, Gibbs faces a Rams defense that was tough against the run last season, allowing only 77.5 rushing yards per game to opposing RBs, ranking 8th in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Gibbs dispelled any draft-day doubts by finishing as fantasy's RB10 in his rookie season. The 12th overall pick in 2023 showcased his explosiveness in a Lions offense that had the second-most RB rushing yards and attempts. Gibbs had six weeks inside the top three at RB, finished second in yards before first contact and was fifth in fantasy points per touch. Despite being in a committee with David Montgomery, Gibbs was also 12th in scrimmage yards, ninth in total touchdowns and top 10 in targets and receptions. All this while ranking 25th among RBs in touches. He won't have the workload of a feature back, but at just 22 years old, Gibbs is already a superstar and should be viewed as a clear top-10 RB.

outlooksByWeek.1: Garrett Wilson will look to breakout for the Jets, starting in Week 1 against the 49ers Monday night. Wilson has turned in consecutive 1,000 yard seasons since being drafted out of Ohio State, both coming with mediocre quarterback play. That could change with Aaron Rodgers now healthy, and seemingly minimal competition for volume targets elsewhere. New York has deep threat Mike Williams currently healthy and a workhorse RB in Breece Hall, but not much else, suggesting Wilson will be peppered early and often. This won't be an easy opener with San Francisco allowing a mere 6.4 ypc and the presence of top CB Charvarius Ward, but Wilson likely embraces that challenge and can produce on volume alone.

player.seasonOutlook: Wilson is entering his third season with the Jets, with fantasy managers eagerly anticipating his breakout season. Since Wilson joined the league, New York's quarterback unit has yet to exceed a passer rating of 75. Despite this, Wilson has already broken the Jets' franchise records for most receiving yards (1,956) and receptions (159) in his first two seasons. He has also maintained an impressive average of 9.2 targets per game, a reliable metric for wide receivers. Even with Mike Williams added to the fold, Wilson has the potential for a career-best performance in 2024 with Aaron Rodgers returning under center. Projected to lead the Jets in targets, Wilson can be confidently drafted as a low-end WR1 in fantasy drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: All eyes will be on Deshaun Watson as he leads the Browns into a Week 1 matchup against the Cowboys. He has failed to meet expectations since joining Cleveland prior to the 2022 season and has spent the entire offseason rehabbing from a shoulder injury. The Cowboys have a defense, and particularly a secondary, known for creating takeaways led by Micah Parsons and the return of Trevon Diggs. They also finished fifth in the league last season by surrendering only 192.1 passing yards per game to opposing quarterbacks. This won't be the easiest matchup for Watson to excel in, and combined with his shaky recent performance and questionable health, it's difficult to envision him turning in a standout stat line to begin 2024.

player.seasonOutlook: Watson is set for his third season in Cleveland and seventh overall as a pro. A 2022 suspension and a shoulder injury last season have limited Watson to only 12 starts with the Browns, in which he has averaged just 14.4 points per game and completed 59.8% of his passes. The team traded for WR Jerry Jeudy this offseason to bolster the pass game opposite Amari Cooper and David Njoku in Kevin Stefanski's quarterback-friendly offense. However, while Watson was playing at a scheme-transcendent level earlier in his career with the Texans, his lack of availability and declining production in Cleveland creates concern and drops his fantasy value into the QB2 range.

outlooksByWeek.1: Davante Adams proved not to be quarterback-proof after all. After back-to-back seasons of over 1,500 receiving yards despite the fact that he was catching passes from the likes of Derek Carr in 2022, Adams saw his numbers plunge in 2023 as Jimmy Garoppolo, Aidan O'Connell and even Brian Hoyer took turns under center for the Raiders. His 6.5 yards per target and 11.1 yards per reception were his worst averages since 2015, although he did manage to catch triple-digit passes for the fourth straight season. Gardner Minshew won a battle in training camp over O'Connell for the starting QB job, which should provide Las Vegas' game with more stability, but at 31 years old, Adams may not be able to rebound without more help from his quarterback than a journeyman like Minshew can provide. Adams will face a Chargers secondary in Week 1 that finished in the bottom four in receiving touchdowns allowed and yards per target allowed to wideouts last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Considering Adams endured three quarterbacks throwing him the football and a midseason coaching change, his 2023 season was probably better than you remember it being. Adams finished 10th among WRs in fantasy points. He got off to a scorching start, with two 20-point performances in his first three weeks, but suffered an inexplicable, mid-year dip in targets just before Josh McDaniels was dispatched. Under Antonio Pierce, Adams finished strong, posting the league's highest target share (36.4%) and five games of 14-plus fantasy points. It was a reminder that Adams is one of the league's true game-changing receivers, independent of who is throwing him the football. He remains a fantasy WR1 entering his age-31 season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chris Olave's hopes of finally emerging as a true alpha wide receiver for the Saints will be put to the test early, with a tough matchup against Carolina's secondary on deck Week 1. The Panthers allowed just 11 touchdowns to the WR position last season, and when top CB Jaycee Horn shadowed Olave in Week 14 last season, he was limited to just four catches for 28 yards on five targets, but salvaged his day with a touchdown. Still, Olave has started his career with back-to-back 1,000-yard seasons, and all he could need for a Year 3 breakout is modest improvement of his own, plus another offseason to have built chemistry with QB Derek Carr. Fellow wideouts Rashid Shaheed and A.T. Perry are most comfortable as deep threats, so if this offense wants to do more than regularly dump off to RB Alvin Kamara, the passing game will have to consistently go through Olave.

player.seasonOutlook: Olave is entering his third NFL season after posting a pair of top-25 fantasy campaigns in his his first two campaigns. The 24 year old saw a boost in targets, receptions, yardage and touchdowns in his second season, finishing top 20 among receivers in all but the latter category. The Saints didn't add any significant target competition for Olave, which means he's a near lock to continue handling a massive workload. More usage near the goal line would get Olave to the next level (14 career end zone targets), but he's a good bet for another 80-catch, 1,000-plus yard season and thus makes for a fringe WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Joe Mixon is set to lead Houston's backfield in Week 1 against a Colts defense that allowed the fifth-most fantasy points to running backs in 2023. The Colts struggled in every facet of defending RBs, allowing the sixth-most rushing yards (1,767), third-most rushing TDs (16) and fourth-most receiving yards (723) to the position. Mixon signed a three-year, $25.5 million contract in March to replace Devin Singletary atop the depth chart. The 28-year-old Mixon exceeded 1,000 rushing yards in four of seven seasons with the Bengals, including a 1,034-yard campaign on the ground in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: After joining the Texans in March via trade, Mixon looks to bring his volume-driven, veteran appeal to an emergent Houston offense. While efficiency wasn't the hallmark of Mixon's final season with the Bengals, he did handle a massive workload en route to finishing sixth in total fantasy points among backs and ninth in per-game production in 2023. The Texans didn't pepper the backfield with many targets last season (28th in the league), but the team did rank 12th in both total carries and red zone totes allocated to backs. Without much competition for snaps, targets or touches present on the depth chart, Mixon is poised for another big role on a team flush with receiving weapons that could yield light opposing boxes.

outlooksByWeek.1: Matthew Stafford seems to be back to full health after spending some time in August dealing with a hamstring injury, and it looks like he'll have his best receiving options available Week 1 when the Rams visit the Lions. The Lions aggressive style under coach Dan Campbell means they were frequently involved in fantasy friendly shootouts at home last season. Detroit allowed 268 passing yards per game in 2023, third worst in the league, but their defense should improve this year after several signings in the secondary. Armed with great receiving weapons in Cooper Kupp and Puka Nacua, Stafford is a solid fantasy option at quarterback.

player.seasonOutlook: Two years removed from a Super Bowl victory and a top-six fantasy finish, Stafford managed a mostly healthy 2023 season, in which he averaged nearly 16 fantasy points per contest. It was a comeback of sorts for the 36-year-old, who missed the final seven games of 2022 with a back injury and was without the pass-catching talents of Cooper Kupp to start 2023. A surprisingly effective performance from the offensive line, as well as the stunning emergence of Puka Nacua, helped Stafford regain his fantasy relevance. The vet heated up as the season progressed, recording five multi-touchdown performances between Weeks 11 and 17 (he registered just one such effort prior to the team's Week 10 bye). He heads into 2024 as an ideal QB2 and superflex target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Deebo Samuel opens the season Week 1 in a tough matchup against a talented Jets secondary that allowed fewer than ten receptions to wide receivers per game in 2023, fewest in the league. The Jets will do well to perform that well against the 49ers this weekend, as coach Kyle Shannahan is never short on ideas to get the ball into Samuel's hands, including giving him over 2 carries per game last season. Samuel is one of the most explosive playmakers in the NFL, averaging 9.0 yards after catch in 2023. Even in a difficult matchup, he is still a solid fantasy option this weekend.

player.seasonOutlook: The 49ers are flush with talent, making each player's volume difficult to predict on a weekly basis. Christian McCaffrey's arrival, however, appears to have had the biggest impact on Samuel, whose rushing opportunities have dwindled from 3.7 per game in 2021 to 2.5 per contest in 2023. Still, the wideback continued to produce for fantasy managers, thriving in the red area of the field with a team-leading number of red zone looks (17) and 12 total TDs (WR4). While durability is a concern, Samuel's versatile usage and overall efficiency provide him with a sky-high ceiling. Target him as a WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Aaron Rodgers returns home with the Jets to face the 49ers in Week 1 Monday night. The 40-year old future Hall of Famer has thrown one pass over the last year and is returning from an Achilles' tear and did not appear in the preseason. He's got weapons and motivation, but chemistry remains unproven. It's a challenging matchup, as San Francisco only allowed 6.4 ypa and 20 touchdown passes against 22 INTs last season. They'll likely have an extra push to get after Rodgers, but with the national spotlight upon him in his return, it's fair to dream big.

player.seasonOutlook: It will be Rodgers' second season with the Jets after an Achilles injury in Week 1 sidelined him for the 2023 campaign. The four-time MVP is entering his age-40 season, but Rodgers averaged 19.9 fantasy points per game in his final three seasons with the Packers. The Jets didn't have a reliable secondary pass-catcher opposite Garrett Wilson last season, so the offseason addition of Mike Williams helps in that area, as does drafting Malachi Corley in the third round. New York's offensive line was also a liability in pass protection, ranking 30th in pass block win rate. The Jets addressed this area by signing former All-Pro offensive tackle Tyron Smith (among others) during free agency. Rodgers has a history of elevating the play of those around him, and he can be drafted as a low-end QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kenneth Walker is set to start in Week 1 in a great matchup against Denver, who had the third worst rushing defense in the league last season. Walker should operate as Seattle's lead back, though Zach Charbonnet will likely spell Walker at points during the game. New offensive coordinator Ryan Grubb has been full of praise for Walker this offseason, explicitly making note of his improvements in pass protection and his abilities as a pass-catcher. Walker is already a strong fantasy option with his ability to rip off long runs, so any additional pass-catching work would serve as a welcome bonus. Denver didn't make many improvements to their defense this offseason after allowing a league high 5.0 yards per rushing attempt in 2023.

player.seasonOutlook: There was concern that Seattle would revert to utilizing an RBBC after selecting UCLA's Zach Charbonnet in the second round of the 2023 draft. While Walker and Charbonnet logged an even number of snaps, Walker remained the team's primary option, averaging nearly 15 carries and two catches per contest for the season. Despite demonstrating high-end burst and change-of-direction ability (72 evaded tackles, RB3), Walker struggled with efficiency (4.1 YPC). His receiving chops also remain in question, as he drew fewer targets and posted a lower catch rate (78.4%, RB22) than the aforementioned Charbonnet. Still, Walker figures to lead Seattle's backfield and should deliver RB2 numbers for fantasy managers in 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Josh Jacobs joins the Packers after a disappointing season with the Raiders, where he rushed for a career-low 805 yards and six touchdowns. His dip in production was due to a combination of lackluster quarterback play, questionable coaching decisions, and missing the final four games of the season due to injury. However, the 26-year-old is only two years removed from leading the NFL with 1,653 rushing yards in 2022 and is expected to serve as a workhorse back in a more formidable Green Bay offense. In Week 1, Jacobs faces a Philadelphia defense that ranked 10th against the run in 2023, allowing 103.4 rushing yards per game.

player.seasonOutlook: Jacobs joins the Packers after spending his first five years with the Raiders. In 2023, Jacobs resumed his go-to-back role and finished second in touches per game. However, despite that volume, Jacobs was RB17 in fantasy points per game, due to career lows in rushing yards, touchdowns and yards per rush. At 26 years old, Jacobs reprises his lead-back duties in Green Bay, replacing Aaron Jones and sharing the backfield with rookie MarShawn Lloyd. Jacobs is one of only five RBs with at least 50 targets in each of the past three seasons, and he gets enough passing-game work to maintain a high weekly floor. With another heavy workload on the horizon, Jacobs is a top-15 running back.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sam Darnold enters Week 1 as the Vikings' starting quarterback after J.J. McCarthy's season-ending meniscus surgery. Despite a history of underwhelming performances, Darnold has an opportunity to succeed with elite targets like Justin Jefferson, Jordan Addison and eventually T.J. Hockenson. He'll face a Giants defense that allowed 229.3 passing yards per game last year, ranking 14th in the NFL. While Darnold's deep passing ability remains questionable, his supporting cast gives him a chance for solid production.

player.seasonOutlook: Darnold signed with the Vikings this offseason, his fourth team in five years, after backing up Brock Purdy in San Francisco last season. With rookie J.J. McCarthy set to miss his rookie season, Darnold is in line to make a majority (if not all) starts for Minnesota this season. Of course, in his six seasons in the league, Darnold has never appeared in more than 13 games, nor has he finished higher than QB28 in fantasy points. Perhaps Kevin O'Connell and a good group of targets can lead Darnold to a surprise breakout season, but he's not worth drafting in standard ESPN leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kyren Williams is expected to be the Rams' primary running back in Week 1, despite the addition of rookie Blake Corum. Williams faces a Lions defense that was strong against the run in 2023, allowing just 3.47 yards per carry. Still, the Rams' matchup against the Lions projects to be high scoring, and the Lions were involved in several shootouts at home last season. Williams may concede some snaps to Corum, but his three-down skill set makes him a solid fantasy option.

player.seasonOutlook: After injuries kept Williams off the field in 2022, he entered his sophomore effort barely drafted by fantasy managers (14th-round ADP in 12-team PPR leagues). That quickly changed as Williams emerged as the Rams' undisputed RB1, averaging nearly 22 touches per contest in his 12 games played. A creative runner with receiving chops and an uncanny nose for the end zone (15 total TDs, third among RBs), Williams turned on the jets down the stretch, posting nearly 24 fantasy points per game from Weeks 12 through 17. He did break his hand during the team's Wild Card game in Detroit, but should be healed up in time for training camp. Fantasy managers will want to keep an eye on rookie Blake Corum's potential ascent, but Williams remains the lead back and is a solid RB1 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Michael Pittman will look to reprise his role as the top option in the Colts' passing attack in Week 1 against a Texans defense that allowed the 12th-most yards but second-fewest touchdowns (10) to wide receivers in 2023. Pittman has averaged 1,053 receiving yards and 4.7 receiving TDs over the past three seasons, but the Texans held him to a total of 100 yards across two meetings last season. Anthony Richardson is back under center for the Colts after suffering a season-ending shoulder in Week 5 last season, and Indianapolis drafted WR Adonai Mitchell in the second round, but WR Josh Downs (ankle) may not be available against the Texans. Pittman figures to see a lot of cornerback Derek Stingley, who had a strong finish to his second NFL season in 2023 after an up-and-down start to his career.

player.seasonOutlook: A steady career progression as a sure-handed receiver earned Pittman a big extension from the Colts heading into his fifth season. The son of a former bruising running back, Pittman handles a physical, possession role that includes rare volume, as he finished ninth in total targets and fifth in receptions in 2023. A touchdown-per-target rate of just 3.1% as a pro and a modest average depth of target clip the past two seasons have resulted in WR2 outcomes for Pittman. As the likely first read for Anthony Richardson on most dropbacks this season, Pittman enters the season with a stable floor for WR2 production and the upside for a new tier of value. Targeting Pittman after the crop of true WR1 options are taken could prove savvy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kirk Cousins' first challenge in his comeback from a serious Achilles injury will be a Steelers defense that ranked sixth in the league last season. If any O-line can protect a non-mobile quarterback from edge rushers T.J. Watt and Alex Highsmith, though, it's Atlanta's, which should provide Cousins with the best pass protection of his NFL career. Cousins was pacing for roughly 5,000 yards and 40 TDs with the Vikings last year, and now armed with one of the league's best skill-position trios of WR Drake London, RB Bijan Robinson, and TE Kyle Pitts, he's in good position in Week 1 to pressure what was a shaky Pittsburgh secondary last season. Expect Cousins to focus on attacking the intermediate area of the field, a gameplan which London's skillset is the perfect match for.

player.seasonOutlook: Cousins signed with the Falcons in March and gives Atlanta some hope after the failed Desmond Ridder experiment of 2023. Cousins got off to a hot start in Minnesota last season, racking up 2,331 passing yards and 18 touchdowns (and just five interceptions) through eight games, but succumbed to a torn Achilles that ended his season at the midpoint. He'll have no shortage of targets to work with in RB Bijan Robinson, WR Drake London and underused TE Kyle Pitts, but his lack of mobility is always a concern. While he's expected to give the Atlanta offense a boost, the 35-year-old pocket passer is a solid QB2 with a ceiling of a fringe QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Trevor Lawrence and the Jaguars open the 2024 season with a Week 1 road matchup against a Dolphins defense that finished in the middle of the pack last season. We could be in for a warm-weather Week 1 shootout in Miami, as the Dolphins will be adjusting to numerous key offseason personnel losses, including CB Xavien Howard, DT Christian Wilkins, LB Jerome Baker and S Brandon Jones. Jacksonville's offense also made some personnel changes, replacing WRs Calvin Ridley and Zay Jones with 23rd overall draft pick Brian Thomas and free-agent signing Gabe Davis. Christian Kirk is back after missing the last five games of 2023 due to a groin injury, though the dependable WR is nursing a calf injury heading into the season opener. RB Travis Etienne and TE Evan Engram are also returning after combining for 172 catches last season.

player.seasonOutlook: Even as we enter the fourth season of Lawrence's career, it's unclear what type of fantasy producer he truly is. Lawrence finished 17th in per-game fantasy production in 2023. Last year also marked the second straight season he finished strong, as the former top pick was sixth among QBs in fantasy points per game from Week 11 on. Gone is last season's leading receiver in Calvin Ridley, but the team still has some savvy skill players to support a return to relevance for the Lawrence in Year 4. While he is talented as a runner, a lack of designed rushing plays and a greater reliance on pocket production has him understandably positioned on the fringes of QB1 and QB2 status as 2024 fantasy drafts approach. It will only take a middle-to-late-round pick to find out if Lawrence can sustain a full season of special production.

outlooksByWeek.1: Marvin Harrison will make his debut for the Cardinals in Week 1 at Buffalo, who were the NFL's sixth best passing defense last year. Harrison is one of the most highly-rated wide receiver prospects ever, and he projects to immediately become Kyler Murray's number one receiving option. He should see plenty of targets in this game, especially if the talented Buffalo offense forces the Cardinals to throw more frequently in a negative game script. Harrison will have a tough task on his hands in his first start facing coverage from talented Bills cornerback duo Taron Johnson and Rasul Douglas. The Bills defense had 16 interceptions and held opponents under 220 receiving yards per game last season.

player.seasonOutlook: A polished playmaker with elite NFL bloodlines, Harrison is arguably the most pro-ready player in this year's draft class, regardless of position. Kyler Murray may not be the most consistent passer in the NFL, but he has proven capable of supporting a top-15 fantasy producer at the position (DeAndre Hopkins was a top-15 WR in fantasy PPG in all three of his seasons as a Cardinal). Harrison should easily emerge as Murray's primary option, likely flirting with double-digit targets on a regular basis and making him a priority rookie in redraft and dynasty formats.
